body:
HWCleanup fails to optimize the following IR:
```mlir
// ./bin/circt-opt -hw-cleanup
hw.module @foo() {
  sv.initial {
    sv.ifdef.procedural "FOO" {
      sv.fwrite "A"
    }
  }
  sv.initial {
    sv.ifdef.procedural "FOO" {
      sv.fwrite "B"
    }
  }
}
```
The current output is:
```mlir
 hw.module @foo() {
    sv.initial  {
      sv.ifdef.procedural "FOO"  {
        sv.fwrite "A"
      }
      sv.ifdef.procedural "FOO"  {
        sv.fwrite "B"
      }
    }
    hw.output
}
``` 
But we want these `sv.idef.procedural` to be merged as well, like:  
```mlir
hw.module @foo() {
    sv.initial  {
      sv.ifdef.procedural "FOO"  {
        sv.fwrite "A"
        sv.fwrite "B"
      }
    }
    hw.output
  }
```
This behavior is because we merge sub regions first:
https://github.com/llvm/circt/blob/853cd4eb3b87db866461fafc1b57e2953a0c99c4/lib/Dialect/SV/Transforms/HWCleanup.cpp#L237-L240 

It can be fixed by changing the order of recursions but it would became O(N^2) time complexity if we do this naively. Therefore we have to do something smart there.
